additional_info:
By customizing and appending the following code to this style, you can also designate local images to fix the buttons with no thumbnail at all. You must have one section like this for each button with a custom background image.

<code>
#newtab-window a.newtab-link[href*="somesite.com"] span.newtab-thumbnail {
    background-image: url("file:///c:/path/to/some/logo.png") !important;
    background-repeat: no-repeat !important;
    background-size: 100% auto !important;
    background-position: center !important;
    background-color: #fff !important;
  }
</code>

I cannot include this in the style itself because this is highly dependent on each user's habits. There must be a section like this for each button that you want to give a custom background. Some users may want to do this for all of their buttons, while others might use it for just one or two buttons. Also, I recommend keeping the images no bigger than twice the size of your buttons.

css:
@-moz-document url("about:newtab") {

  #newtab-window .newtab-cell,
  #newtab-window .newtab-site,
  #newtab-window .newtab-site:hover,
  #newtab-window .newtab-cell:hover {
    background-color: transparent !important;
    border-radius: 12px !important;
  }

  #newtab-window a.newtab-link span.newtab-thumbnail {
   background-position: center !important;
   border-radius: 12px !important;
  }

  #newtab-window a.newtab-link span.newtab-title {
    visibility: hidden !important;
    background-color: rgba(25, 25, 25, 0.65) !important;
    color: rgb(255, 255, 0) !important;
    font-weight: bold !important;
    border-radius: 12px !important;
    width: 85% !important;
    margin-left: auto !important;
    margin-right: auto !important;
    bottom: 4px !important;
  }

  #newtab-window a.newtab-link:hover span.newtab-title {
    visibility: visible !important;
  }
}
